    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc_zs.00578.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="printed"/>Medical Superintendent's</name>
                    <name type="place">Office.</name>
                    <name type="place">INSANE ASYLUM</name> 
                    <name type="place">LONDON ONTARIO<ptr target="loc.08207_n1"/></name>
                    <date when="1891-11-24"><handShift rend="manuscript"/>24 Nov <handShift rend="printed"/>18<handShift rend="manuscript"/>91</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener> 
            <p>Yours of 22<hi rend="underline">d</hi> just to hand.<ptr target="loc.08207_n2"/> I am much relieved to hear so good an 
                account of the tomb<ptr target="loc.07740_n6"/> settlement or probability of settlement. I think your offer is very fair and I 
             expect they will accept it&#8212;I am sure Harned<ptr target="loc.03745_n1"/> 
                will secure you a fair deal. So the English folk want to buy the American copy 
              right?<ptr target="loc.04804_n3"/> If 
            I were you I would sell it&#8212;so much down and a small sum per vol. (3, 4 or 5 p.c. of 
            selling price) or sell for cash out and out. The book will never be published untill some 
            good house gets control of it and has an interest in showing it&#8212;I would stipulate 
            for no changes in the text and let her go. The book is finished now<ptr target="loc.04811_n6"/>&#8212;let it be 
            given to the world&#8212;at present the world knows nothing about it and it never will if 
            D. <choice><sic>Mackay</sic><corr>McKay</corr></choice><ptr target="nyp.00580_n3"/> continues to handle it.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute>With best love&#8212;So long!</salute>
                <signed>R M Bucke</signed> 
            </closer> 
